    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT266-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">varaiyātu pirintaviṭattat tōḻikkuk kiḻatti uraittatu</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told by HER to the confidante when he had separated
          without marrying. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT266">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> namakkoṉ ṟuraiyā rāyiṉun tamakkoṉ</l>
          <l> ṟiṉṉā viravi ṉiṉṟuṇai yākiya</l>
          <l> paṭappai vēṅkaikku maṟantaṉar kollō</l>
          <l> maṟapparum paṇaittōḷ marīit</l>
          <l> tuṟattal valliyōr puḷvāyt tūtē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent2">Even if he didn't tell us a thing,<note place="foot">Here and in the
            following line Cām./T.V.G. explain <term xml:lang="ta">oṉṟu </term> as the verbal root
            "to be one", that is, the message suitable to us/to the Vēṅkai tree.</note> </l>
          <l>did he forget the message in a bird's mouth,<note place="foot">Here, as often, the
            circular construction means that the confusing word order is explained at the very end:
            the last line contains subject and direct object.</note></l>
          <l rend="indent">for the Vēṅkai tree in the garden that was the one dear companion</l>
          <l rend="indent2">to him in undear night, he who was able to abandon [us],</l>
          <l rend="indent3">after joining with [my] bamboo shoulders</l>
          <l rend="indent8">[that are] difficult to forget?</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
